Desai","email":"bbcec020b514464468c6a99414de2031b1a0cc8b@gmail.com"},"message":"[ROCm] Update script install_pip_packages.sh for Python 2.7

Currently ROCm TF cotnainers use the `install_pip_packages.sh` script to install the Python pip package-manager.
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/Dockerfile.rocm#L102
* https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/tools/ci_build/install/install_pip_packages.sh#L20-L23

Starting 01/23/2021, we started getting the following error while building TF containers for ROCM CI (when calling `get-pip.py` for Python2)

```
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "get-pip.py", line 24226, in <module>
    main()
  File "get-pip.py", line 199, in main
    bootstrap(tmpdir=tmpdir)
  File "get-pip.py", line 82, in bootstrap
    from pip._internal.cli.main import main as pip_entry_point
  File "/tmp/tmpWkL0gn/pip.zip/pip/_internal/cli/main.py", line 60
    sys.stderr.write(f"ERROR: {exc}")
```

The cause seems to be an update to the `get-pip.py` script, which now picks the version `pip-21.0` (previously it was `pip-20.3.4`).
`pip-21.0` drops support for Python2.7 (as indicated by the following warning message)
```
DEPRECATION: Python 2.7 reached the end of its life on January 1st, 2020.
Please upgrade your Python as Python 2.7 is no longer maintained.
pip 21.0 will drop support for Python 2.7 in January 2021.
More details about Python 2 support in pip can be found at
https://pip.pypa.io/en/latest/development/release-process/#python-2-support
pip 21.0 will remove support for this functionality.
```

It seems that there is now a Python 2.7 specific version of the `get-pip.py` script that we need to use, and that is what this commit does","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mansnils/tensorflow/commits/5a3ac7eea0cb61af8e0d25419b174ead0a6a73ac"},{"sha":"dde133c3f3edc717b0fa2b08f798e0d6c473d8bc","author":{"name":"Trent Lo","email":"7ddb1753734378bc8a5ee2f8f682002ac2d0087e@nvidia.com"},"message":"Fixing a bug that concat can create extra constraints to buffer sharing.

Input TF executor dialect:

lowered TFRT CoreRT dialect:
%idx_int = corert.tensorhandle_to_int32 %idx
%out_chain, %outputs = tfrt.case %idx_int [@branch0, @branch1] (%chain, ...)

We approximate it with:
expm1 = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 5e-7 or about nine ULPs when
compared against libm.

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

Fixes a couple bugs related to getting and setting vocabs:
 - set_vocabulary can now be called if num_oov_indices > 1
 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

Change-Id: I7430588bc88c8b9d066c49651ee418fc33e08d28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/icpm/tensorflow/commits/ac3abfbaa1577c8bbfb52e8927d485f2cd13fb56"},{"sha":"86d8b31314bf815d10ee8ad92a139b198e598ce5","author":{"name":"Matt Watson","email":"1a665c2a0e9d672d25454bd51a7db62c9997cd45@google.com"},"message":"Align vocab indices for keras preprocessing lookup layers when invert=True

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

Fixes a couple bugs related to getting and setting vocabs:
 - set_vocabulary can now be called if num_oov_indices > 1
 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355556020
Change-Id: I29a2cbc5f3cfb45721907354287b086703a0314b","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/57db297c71026f6c388484fbcfc391e426062831"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

Benefit is set to the number of ops a pattern targets which is one for this pattern. Native MLIR patterns for an op will be still be preferred over this generic pattern matching any op.

This allows some native pattern to set benefit zero to prefer the fallback pattern over the native one where applicable.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

Example:
Input TF executor dialect:
%outputs, %control = tf_executor.island wraps "tf.Case"(%arg, ...) {branches = [@branch0, @branch1], ...}

lowered TFRT CoreRT dialect:
%idx_int = corert.tensorhandle_to_int32 %idx
%out_chain, %outputs = tfrt.case %idx_int [@branch0, @branch1] (%chain, ...)

Disable a Python test since TFRT doesn't support lowering v1 control flow ops ("_SwitchN" in this test).

Lowering MLIR unit test added at third_party/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tfrt/tests/tf_to_corert/control_flow.mlir.

Example:
Input TF executor dialect:
%outputs, %control = tf_executor.island wraps "tf.Case"(%arg, ...) {branches = [@branch0, @branch1], ...}

lowered TFRT CoreRT dialect:
%idx_int = corert.tensorhandle_to_int32 %idx
%out_chain, %outputs = tfrt.case %idx_int [@branch0, @branch1] (%chain, ...)

Disable a Python test since TFRT doesn't support lowering v1 control flow ops ("_SwitchN" in this test).

Lowering MLIR unit test added at third_party/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tfrt/tests/tf_to_corert/control_flow.mlir.

Change-Id: I7430588bc88c8b9d066c49651ee418fc33e08d28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KaycoinsInc/tensorflow/commits/ac3abfbaa1577c8bbfb52e8927d485f2cd13fb56"},{"sha":"86d8b31314bf815d10ee8ad92a139b198e598ce5","author":{"name":"Matt Watson","email":"1a665c2a0e9d672d25454bd51a7db62c9997cd45@google.com"},"message":"Align vocab indices for keras preprocessing lookup layers when invert=True

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

Fixes a couple bugs related to getting and setting vocabs:
 - set_vocabulary can now be called if num_oov_indices > 1
 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

Example:
Input TF executor dialect:

lowered TFRT CoreRT dialect:
%idx_int = corert.tensorhandle_to_int32 %idx

We approximate it with:
expm1 = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 5e-7 or about nine ULPs when
compared against libm.

[{"sha":"8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/terraform/commits/8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c"},{"sha":"7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Experimental "terraform test" command

This is just a prototype to gather some feedback in our ongoing research
on integration testing of Terraform modules. The hope is that by having a
command integrated into Terraform itself it'll be easier for interested
module authors to give it a try, and also easier for us to iterate quickly
based on feedback without having to coordinate across multiple codebases.

Everything about this is subject to change even in future patch releases.
Since it's a CLI command rather than a configuration language feature it's
not using the language experiments mechanism, but generates a warning
similar to the one language experiments generate in order to be clear that
backward compatibility is not guaranteed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/terraform/commits/7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e"},{"sha":"8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Initial docs for the module integration testing experiment

Since this is still at an early phase and likely to change significantly
in future iterations, rather than attempting to guess on a suitable final
location for documenting the testing feature I've instead taken the
unusual approach of adding a new page that is explicitly about the
experiment. My expectation is that once we conclude the experiment we'll
replace this new page with a stub that just explains that there was once
an experiment and then links to whatever final feature unfolded from the
research.

The URL for this page is hard-coded into the warning message in the
"terraform test" command, so as we continue to evolve this feature in
future releases we'll need to update the callout note on the page about
which Terraform CLI version it's currently talking about, so users of
older versions can clearly see when they'd need to upgrade in order to
participate in a later incarnation of the experiment.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/terraform/commits/8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378"},{"sha":"62b4d7b92c459ac3544e3a2c788142a1a8c058c0","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/waterdrops/terraform/commits/62b4d7b92c459ac3544e3a2c788142a1a8c058c0"}]

Change-Id: I519ea4f6cd070cdfc1c1f21cce174e1c1aff5dd0","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/44469a6e8e6dd8aad41b6ad2c8f73a6ada67a544"},{"sha":"16e48a89987625c54716026765fa378601301224","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Make compression configurable.

Previously, the tf.data service would always perform Snappy compression. Now the user has the option to disable compression, which can save CPU and memory bandwidth for data that doesn't compress well. Disabling compression also benefits alternative data transfer mechanisms, giving them direct access to the Tensors that need to be transferred.

This CL opts not to add a `compression` argument to the `register_dataset` and `from_dataset_id` methods. In a later CL, registered datasets can store metadata about whether they are (optionally) compressed, so that `from_dataset_id` can infer whether uncompression is needed without the user having to specify it in the API.

[{"sha":"8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c"},{"sha":"7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Experimental "terraform test" command

This is just a prototype to gather some feedback in our ongoing research
on integration testing of Terraform modules. The hope is that by having a
command integrated into Terraform itself it'll be easier for interested
module authors to give it a try, and also easier for us to iterate quickly
based on feedback without having to coordinate across multiple codebases.

Everything about this is subject to change even in future patch releases.
Since it's a CLI command rather than a configuration language feature it's
not using the language experiments mechanism, but generates a warning
similar to the one language experiments generate in order to be clear that
backward compatibility is not guaranteed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e"},{"sha":"8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Initial docs for the module integration testing experiment

Since this is still at an early phase and likely to change significantly
in future iterations, rather than attempting to guess on a suitable final
location for documenting the testing feature I've instead taken the
unusual approach of adding a new page that is explicitly about the
experiment. My expectation is that once we conclude the experiment we'll
replace this new page with a stub that just explains that there was once
an experiment and then links to whatever final feature unfolded from the
research.

The URL for this page is hard-coded into the warning message in the
"terraform test" command, so as we continue to evolve this feature in
future releases we'll need to update the callout note on the page about
which Terraform CLI version it's currently talking about, so users of
older versions can clearly see when they'd need to upgrade in order to
participate in a later incarnation of the experiment.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378"},{"sha":"62b4d7b92c459ac3544e3a2c788142a1a8c058c0","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/62b4d7b92c459ac3544e3a2c788142a1a8c058c0"}]

[{"sha":"8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c"},{"sha":"7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Experimental "terraform test" command

This is just a prototype to gather some feedback in our ongoing research
on integration testing of Terraform modules. The hope is that by having a
command integrated into Terraform itself it'll be easier for interested
module authors to give it a try, and also easier for us to iterate quickly
based on feedback without having to coordinate across multiple codebases.

Everything about this is subject to change even in future patch releases.
Since it's a CLI command rather than a configuration language feature it's
not using the language experiments mechanism, but generates a warning
similar to the one language experiments generate in order to be clear that
backward compatibility is not guaranteed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e"},{"sha":"8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Initial docs for the module integration testing experiment

Since this is still at an early phase and likely to change significantly
in future iterations, rather than attempting to guess on a suitable final
location for documenting the testing feature I've instead taken the
unusual approach of adding a new page that is explicitly about the
experiment. My expectation is that once we conclude the experiment we'll
replace this new page with a stub that just explains that there was once
an experiment and then links to whatever final feature unfolded from the
research.

The URL for this page is hard-coded into the warning message in the
"terraform test" command, so as we continue to evolve this feature in
future releases we'll need to update the callout note on the page about
which Terraform CLI version it's currently talking about, so users of
older versions can clearly see when they'd need to upgrade in order to
participate in a later incarnation of the experiment.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378"},{"sha":"62b4d7b92c459ac3544e3a2c788142a1a8c058c0","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/avmi/terraform/commits/62b4d7b92c459ac3544e3a2c788142a1a8c058c0"}]

Change-Id: I7430588bc88c8b9d066c49651ee418fc33e08d28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/osmaelo/tensorflow/commits/ac3abfbaa1577c8bbfb52e8927d485f2cd13fb56"},{"sha":"86d8b31314bf815d10ee8ad92a139b198e598ce5","author":{"name":"Matt Watson","email":"1a665c2a0e9d672d25454bd51a7db62c9997cd45@google.com"},"message":"Align vocab indices for keras preprocessing lookup layers when invert=True

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

Fixes a couple bugs related to getting and setting vocabs:
 - set_vocabulary can now be called if num_oov_indices > 1
 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

The goal is to simplify our CI pipeline so that all configurations
are built and tested in a single workflow.

As a first step, this adds a new build script entry point that builds
both the experimental and stable release channels into a single
artifacts directory.

The script works by wrapping the existing build script (which only
builds a single release channel at a time), then post-processing the
results to match the desired filesystem layout. A future version of the
build script would output the files directly without post-processing.

Because many parts of our infra depend on the existing layout of the
build artifacts directory, I have left the old workflows untouched.
We can incremental migrate to the new layout, then delete the old
workflows after we've finished.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/afzaalahmad/react/commits/eb0fb382308f18460844d646dada2e564f82353d"},{"sha":"9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate build tests to combined workflow (#20574)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/afzaalahmad/react/commits/9a6a41d108e1bb7c4babebebad7e72daa22a2374"},{"sha":"b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate remaining tests to combined workflow (#20577)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/afzaalahmad/react/commits/b99ac3d6dffbe57f94d368cc4f4e0ddf089e4f53"},{"sha":"e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Update package.json versions as part of build step (#20579)

Fixes issue in the new build workflow where the experimental packages do
not include "experimental" in the version string. This was because the
previous approach relied on the RELEASE_CHANNEL environment variable,
which we are no longer setting in the outer CI job, since we use the
same job to build both channels. To solve, I moved the version
post-processing into the build script itself.

Only affects the new build workflow. Old workflow is unchanged.

Longer term, I would like to remove version numbers from the source
entirely, including the package.jsons. We should use a placeholder
instead; that's mostly how it already works, since the release script
swaps out the versions before we publish to stable.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/afzaalahmad/react/commits/e6ed2bcf424d0a25a8f628f7bb9962a29ec7d88f"},{"sha":"fc07b070a09396e60126dd75641472f0c7504edf","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Retry with fresh otp if publish fails (#20582)

We need to call `detachFiberAfterEffects` on the fiber's alternate to
clean it up. We're currently not, because the `alternate` field is
cleared during `detachFiberMutation`. So I deferred detaching the
`alternate` until the passive phase. Only the `return` pointer needs to
be detached for semantic purposes.

I don't think there's any good way to test this without using
reflection. It's not even observable using out our "supported"
reflection APIs (`findDOMNode`), or at least not that I can think of.
Which is a good thing, in a way.

It's not really a memory leak, either, because the only reference to the
alternate fiber is from the parent's alternate. Which will be
disconnected the next time the parent is updated or deleted.

It's really only observable if you mess around with internals in ways
you're not supposed to — I found it because a product test in www that
uses Enzyme was doing just that.

In lieu of a new unit test, I confirmed this patch fixes the broken
product test.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/afzaalahmad/react/commits/42e04b46d19648968537a404f15cebc42b6fab54"},{"sha":"98313aaa7ea58d49eb30ecffc0f9eb6fc1ef467a","author":{"name":"Andrew Clark","email":"46f1a0bd5592a2f9244ca321b129902a06b53e03@andrewclark.io"},"message":"Migrate prepare-release-from-ci to new workflow (#20581)

either "stable" or "experimental", because every build job now includes
both channels.

The prepare-release-from-npm script is unchanged since those releases
are downloaded from npm, nt CI.

(As a side note, I think we should start preparing semver releases using

DevTools was built with a fork of an early idea for how Suspense cache might work. This idea is incompatible with newer APIs like `useTransition` which unfortunately prevented me from making certain UX improvements. This PR swaps out the primary usage of this cache (there are a few) in favor of the newer `unstable_getCacheForType` and `unstable_useCacheRefresh` APIs. We can go back and update the others in follow up PRs.

### Messaging changes

I've refactored the way the frontend loads component props/state/etc to hopefully make it better match the Suspense+cache model. Doing this gave up some of the small optimizations I'd added but hopefully the actual performance impact of that is minor and the overall ergonomic improvements of working with the cache API make this worth it.

The backend no longer remembers inspected paths. Instead, the frontend sends them every time and the backend sends a response with those paths. I've also added a new "force" parameter that the frontend can use to tell the backend to send a response even if the component hasn't rendered since the last time it asked. (This is used to get data for newly inspected paths.)

_Initial inspection..._
```
front |                                                      | back
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:true) ---------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes with no updates..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:[], force:false) --------> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (no-change) -- |
```
_User clicks to expand a path, aka hydrate..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:true) ----> |
      | <------------------------ "inspected" (full-data) -- |
```
_1 second passes during which there is an update..._
```
      | -- "inspect" (id:1, paths:['foo'], force:false) ---> |
      | <----------------- "inspectedElement" (full-data) -- |
```

### Clear errors/warnings transition
Previously this meant there would be a delay after clicking the "clear" button. The UX after this change is much improved.

### Hydrating paths transition
I also added a transition to hydration (expanding "dehyrated" paths).

### Better error boundaries
I also added a lower-level error boundary in case the new suspense operation ever failed. It provides a better "retry" mechanism (select a new element) so DevTools doesn't become entirely useful. Here I'm intentionally causing an error every time I select an element.

### Improved snapshot tests
I also migrated several of the existing snapshot tests to use inline snapshots and added a new serializer for dehydrated props. Inline snapshots are easier to verify and maintain and the new serializer means dehydrated props will be formatted in a way that makes sense rather than being empty (in external snapshots) or super verbose (default inline snapshot format).","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/afzaalahmad/react/commits/af16f755dc7e0d6e2b4bf79b86c434f4ce0497fe"},{"sha":"ba9582da27481677cdac2dd000a438147a5df88e","author":{"name":"ChenLei","email":"2078e632128f17c4aa4e413d134a36c7418bccff@qq.com"},"message":"[devtools] Fix can't expand prop value in some scenario (#20534)

Change-Id: I69676059ce86a50c27bc08d86b4cf07df62bf226","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/ea122ccc6f4f6e0c683c3294004be03c07aeb2c2"},{"sha":"e060146984b22181f0a7cce37ef7c40ae4bfcf20","author":{"name":"Chuanhao Zhuge","email":"2df560f87cba785bae78536bb6567a32ee2f9ce7@google.com"},"message":"[TFRT] Lower tf.Case to tfrt.case.

Example:
Input TF executor dialect:
%outputs, %control = tf_executor.island wraps "tf.Case"(%arg, ...) {branches = [@branch0, @branch1], ...}

lowered TFRT CoreRT dialect:
%idx_int = corert.tensorhandle_to_int32 %idx

[{"sha":"1cd1925acd6c36ccdca51aca62ca6b24b2559a6f","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"64b2b6d12bfe4baae7dad3d018f8cbf6b0e7a044@gone.nl"},"message":"oci.Device() fix FileMode to match runtime spec

The runtime spec expects the FileMode field to only hold file permissions,
however `unix.Stat_t.Mode` contains both file type and mode.

This patch strips file type so that only file mode is included in the Device.

Thanks to Iceber Gu, who noticed the same issue in containerd and runc.

This commit changes scheduling profiler marks from a format like '--schedule-render-1' to '--schedule-render-1-Sync' (where 1 is the numeric value of the Sync lane). This will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. These are no-ops for us, but adding recognition of the event type will prevent profiles imported from e.g. Chrome Canary from throwing with an 'unrecognized event' error. [{"sha":"e5f6b91d294d0c1260ce5079ed0192b43ccd3e82","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add Lane labels to scheduling profiler marks (#20808)

This commit changes scheduling profiler marks from a format like '--schedule-render-1' to '--schedule-render-1-Sync' (where 1 is the numeric value of the Sync lane). This will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. These are no-ops for us, but adding recognition of the event type will prevent profiles imported from e.g. Chrome Canary from throwing with an 'unrecognized event' error. attributes or incorrect types, notify users that the schema stored in

`terraform show -json` to display the current state, or

Although we don't typically do configuration-level string wrangling
directly in Terraform, we delegate to several other upstream libraries
that do. These upgrades all switch to newer versions that support the
latest definitions from Unicode 13, primarily affecting operations such
as converting strings to upper/lowercase or splitting strings into
component characters (substr, reverse, etc).

The tests for the upstream libraries didn't show any regressions from
these updates, so the Unicode 13 changes seem to be backward-compatible
additions rather than significant breaking changes.

(Our go.mod file had also become non-canonical in some ways, and the Go
toolchain fixed that as part of this work, causing a few extra style-only
diffs here that shouldn't cause any change in behavior.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/5f3fb00af5376fb3952b58da0eff6be52f920ffd"},{"sha":"c103242bef596c81171ac035511059918be3a728","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27885 from hashicorp/jbardin/show-json

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358956636
Change-Id: I7430588bc88c8b9d066c49651ee418fc33e08d28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/ac3abfbaa1577c8bbfb52e8927d485f2cd13fb56"},{"sha":"86d8b31314bf815d10ee8ad92a139b198e598ce5","author":{"name":"Matt Watson","email":"1a665c2a0e9d672d25454bd51a7db62c9997cd45@google.com"},"message":"Align vocab indices for keras preprocessing lookup layers when invert=True

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

Fixes a couple bugs related to getting and setting vocabs:
 - set_vocabulary can now be called if num_oov_indices > 1
 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

PiperOrigin-RevId: 358956636
Change-Id: I7430588bc88c8b9d066c49651ee418fc33e08d28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/joshrose/tensorflow/commits/ac3abfbaa1577c8bbfb52e8927d485f2cd13fb56"},{"sha":"86d8b31314bf815d10ee8ad92a139b198e598ce5","author":{"name":"Matt Watson","email":"1a665c2a0e9d672d25454bd51a7db62c9997cd45@google.com"},"message":"Align vocab indices for keras preprocessing lookup layers when invert=True

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

Change-Id: I7430588bc88c8b9d066c49651ee418fc33e08d28","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/KabirKwatra/tensorflow/commits/ac3abfbaa1577c8bbfb52e8927d485f2cd13fb56"},{"sha":"86d8b31314bf815d10ee8ad92a139b198e598ce5","author":{"name":"Matt Watson","email":"1a665c2a0e9d672d25454bd51a7db62c9997cd45@google.com"},"message":"Align vocab indices for keras preprocessing lookup layers when invert=True

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

Fixes a couple bugs related to getting and setting vocabs:

 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small

We approximate it with:
expm1 = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 5e-7 or about nine ULPs when
compared against libm.

  arg() or output() maps to which arg or result number of the custom call.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"[XLA:CPU] More accurate expm1 when x is small

We approximate it with:
expm1 = tanh(x/2)*(exp(x)+1)

Additional care is taken to handle the case when x/2 underflows but x does not
by simply approximating the result with x itself.

This suffices to get us within a relative error of 5e-7 or about nine ULPs when
compared against libm.

- XLA:HLO -> LMHLO conversion drops all token arguments and return values, however
  custom calls that users write still expect to get buffer pointers for these token types.
- To be able to support this, add an optional call target argument mapping attribute to
  LMHLO custom calls. When this attribute is present, it indicates the number of
  arguments and returns that the custom call expects and also indicates which LMHLO
  arg() or output() maps to which arg or result number of the custom call.

Fixes a couple bugs related to getting and setting vocabs:

 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

[{"sha":"42dba8c3f9a821c64864c49e60fff9b3ba3e86c5","author":{"name":"Rob Cowsill","email":"4ced00c28ea0046018d361ef4a0a1cf292775363@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix spurious error from "docker load"

"docker load" validates parent links by comparing image histories, and the
History struct has a time.Time member "Created". Time.UnmarshalJSON can read
RFC3339 timestamps with offset "+00:00", but t.MarshalJSON writes them with
offset "Z". Equivalent times in these two formats are not equal when compared
with the == operator.

This causes checkValidParent to incorrectly return false when the parent image
history contains times using offset "+00:00". In that case the history copied
to the child image will have been converted into "Z" form when marshaled out.

This patch adds an "Equal" method to History, which compares "Created" times
with t.Equal. This is used instead of reflect.DeepEqual in checkValidParent.

The runtime spec expects the FileMode field to only hold file permissions,
however `unix.Stat_t.Mode` contains both file type and mode.

This patch strips file type so that only file mode is included in the Device.

Thanks to Iceber Gu, who noticed the same issue in containerd and runc.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. Now that the possibility of extra provider nodes being added is gone, we
can skip the separate handling of configuration_aliases in the
ProviderConfigTransformer. Instead of adding concrete provider nodes for
configuration_aliases (which could be surprising later as the code
evolves), we implicitly add them based on the providers being passed in
by the parent module, using the same mechanism as non-aliased providers.

Although we don't typically do configuration-level string wrangling
directly in Terraform, we delegate to several other upstream libraries
that do. These upgrades all switch to newer versions that support the
latest definitions from Unicode 13, primarily affecting operations such
as converting strings to upper/lowercase or splitting strings into
component characters (substr, reverse, etc).

The tests for the upstream libraries didn't show any regressions from
these updates, so the Unicode 13 changes seem to be backward-compatible
additions rather than significant breaking changes.

(Our go.mod file had also become non-canonical in some ways, and the Go
toolchain fixed that as part of this work, causing a few extra style-only
diffs here that shouldn't cause any change in behavior.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MartiUK/terraform/commits/5f3fb00af5376fb3952b58da0eff6be52f920ffd"},{"sha":"c103242bef596c81171ac035511059918be3a728","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27885 from hashicorp/jbardin/show-json

Although we don't typically do configuration-level string wrangling
directly in Terraform, we delegate to several other upstream libraries
that do. These upgrades all switch to newer versions that support the
latest definitions from Unicode 13, primarily affecting operations such
as converting strings to upper/lowercase or splitting strings into
component characters (substr, reverse, etc).

The tests for the upstream libraries didn't show any regressions from
these updates, so the Unicode 13 changes seem to be backward-compatible
additions rather than significant breaking changes.

(Our go.mod file had also become non-canonical in some ways, and the Go
toolchain fixed that as part of this work, causing a few extra style-only
diffs here that shouldn't cause any change in behavior.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dweomer/terraform/commits/5f3fb00af5376fb3952b58da0eff6be52f920ffd"},{"sha":"c103242bef596c81171ac035511059918be3a728","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27885 from hashicorp/jbardin/show-json

attributes or incorrect types, notify users that the schema stored in

`terraform show -json` to display the current state, or

Although we don't typically do configuration-level string wrangling
directly in Terraform, we delegate to several other upstream libraries
that do. These upgrades all switch to newer versions that support the
latest definitions from Unicode 13, primarily affecting operations such
as converting strings to upper/lowercase or splitting strings into
component characters (substr, reverse, etc).

The tests for the upstream libraries didn't show any regressions from
these updates, so the Unicode 13 changes seem to be backward-compatible
additions rather than significant breaking changes.

(Our go.mod file had also become non-canonical in some ways, and the Go
toolchain fixed that as part of this work, causing a few extra style-only
diffs here that shouldn't cause any change in behavior.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/5f3fb00af5376fb3952b58da0eff6be52f920ffd"},{"sha":"c103242bef596c81171ac035511059918be3a728","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27885 from hashicorp/jbardin/show-json

Change-Id: I29a2cbc5f3cfb45721907354287b086703a0314b","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/57db297c71026f6c388484fbcfc391e426062831"},{"sha":"92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Set benefit of tf2xla fallback pattern to one

PiperOrigin-RevId: 355563001
Change-Id: Iaf4215b70ed46937e6959efad3e6ea79b24b898a","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/yair-ehrenwald/tensorflow/commits/92984177b355b8acd33c2967b4f473627da7aa26"},{"sha":"d5727f7c236b0be4292bb8fc7929a40592b48f0b","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Prefer fallback pattern for BatchMatMulV2 op legalization to HLO

Fallback pattern avoids broadcast of operands and is therefore faster and should be preferred over the native pattern when possible. We can't disable the native pattern as other projects rely on that for dynamic shaped operands. Added a TODO to bridge this gap within MLIR. Having this option could be useful in the future to quickly fix any correctness or performance issues in legalization by enabling fallback pattern for it.

Setting pattern benefit of the fallback pattern to one and then changing BatchMatMulV2 native legalization benefit to zero. This could have some unintended consequences so running the global TAP to be sure but I expect this to be safe as,

* Very few ops have both fallback and native patterns and fallback patterns are still verified so shouldn't have correctness issues.
* Op specific patterns are preferred over patterns that can match any op if both have the same benefit regardless of the order of patterns.

This change ensures that lookup layers with equal configs and vocabs will use the same indexing when doing forward and inverse lookups. It also adds support for any value of num_oov_indices when invert=True.

Fixes a couple bugs related to getting and setting vocabs:
 - set_vocabulary can now be called if num_oov_indices > 1
 - get_vocabulary will return correct results when num_oov_indices > 1

Fix the logic to add proxy provider nodes for implicitly passed in
providers. The missing continue allowed multiple nodes satisfying the
same provider address to be added to the graph. When attaching the
providers to resources, the fist one encountered would be used, which

default providers is discovered and connected in the ProviderTransformer

Now that the possibility of extra provider nodes being added is gone, we
can skip the separate handling of configuration_aliases in the
ProviderConfigTransformer. Instead of adding concrete provider nodes for
configuration_aliases (which could be surprising later as the code
evolves), we implicitly add them based on the providers being passed in
by the parent module, using the same mechanism as non-aliased providers.

We can know that the `providers` map will be populated, because the
provider structures are validated while loading the configuration.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/8c1703d8df67bc3cb134af58cdea0dded438d617"},{"sha":"dd5227a3bee9cadefa4f1bdae6f28946ed33d130","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"provider transformer tests

There is no longer any concept of a "parent provider". Inheritance of
default providers is discovered and connected in the ProviderTransformer

Now that the possibility of extra provider nodes being added is gone, we
can skip the separate handling of configuration_aliases in the
ProviderConfigTransformer. Instead of adding concrete provider nodes for
configuration_aliases (which could be surprising later as the code
evolves), we implicitly add them based on the providers being passed in
by the parent module, using the same mechanism as non-aliased providers.

We can know that the `providers` map will be populated, because the
provider structures are validated while loading the configuration.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/8c1703d8df67bc3cb134af58cdea0dded438d617"},{"sha":"dd5227a3bee9cadefa4f1bdae6f28946ed33d130","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"provider transformer tests

Although we don't typically do configuration-level string wrangling
directly in Terraform, we delegate to several other upstream libraries
that do. These upgrades all switch to newer versions that support the
latest definitions from Unicode 13, primarily affecting operations such
as converting strings to upper/lowercase or splitting strings into
component characters (substr, reverse, etc).

The tests for the upstream libraries didn't show any regressions from
these updates, so the Unicode 13 changes seem to be backward-compatible
additions rather than significant breaking changes.

(Our go.mod file had also become non-canonical in some ways, and the Go
toolchain fixed that as part of this work, causing a few extra style-only
diffs here that shouldn't cause any change in behavior.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/18562a995f2622b07a386de089f79287ff23ac94"}]

[{"sha":"8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/terraform/commits/8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c"},{"sha":"7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Experimental "terraform test" command

This is just a prototype to gather some feedback in our ongoing research
on integration testing of Terraform modules. The hope is that by having a
command integrated into Terraform itself it'll be easier for interested
module authors to give it a try, and also easier for us to iterate quickly
based on feedback without having to coordinate across multiple codebases.

Everything about this is subject to change even in future patch releases.
Since it's a CLI command rather than a configuration language feature it's
not using the language experiments mechanism, but generates a warning
similar to the one language experiments generate in order to be clear that
backward compatibility is not guaranteed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/terraform/commits/7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e"},{"sha":"8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Initial docs for the module integration testing experiment

Since this is still at an early phase and likely to change significantly
in future iterations, rather than attempting to guess on a suitable final
location for documenting the testing feature I've instead taken the
unusual approach of adding a new page that is explicitly about the
experiment. My expectation is that once we conclude the experiment we'll
replace this new page with a stub that just explains that there was once
an experiment and then links to whatever final feature unfolded from the
research.

The URL for this page is hard-coded into the warning message in the
"terraform test" command, so as we continue to evolve this feature in
future releases we'll need to update the callout note on the page about
which Terraform CLI version it's currently talking about, so users of
older versions can clearly see when they'd need to upgrade in order to
participate in a later incarnation of the experiment.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/terraform/commits/8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378"},{"sha":"62b4d7b92c459ac3544e3a2c788142a1a8c058c0","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"Update CHANGELOG.md","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/terraform/commits/62b4d7b92c459ac3544e3a2c788142a1a8c058c0"}]

[{"sha":"8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c"},{"sha":"7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Experimental "terraform test" command

This is just a prototype to gather some feedback in our ongoing research
on integration testing of Terraform modules. The hope is that by having a
command integrated into Terraform itself it'll be easier for interested
module authors to give it a try, and also easier for us to iterate quickly
based on feedback without having to coordinate across multiple codebases.

Everything about this is subject to change even in future patch releases.
Since it's a CLI command rather than a configuration language feature it's
not using the language experiments mechanism, but generates a warning
similar to the one language experiments generate in order to be clear that
backward compatibility is not guaranteed.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e"},{"sha":"8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Initial docs for the module integration testing experiment

Since this is still at an early phase and likely to change significantly
in future iterations, rather than attempting to guess on a suitable final
location for documenting the testing feature I've instead taken the
unusual approach of adding a new page that is explicitly about the

[{"sha":"8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c"},{"sha":"7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Experimental "terraform test" command

This is just a prototype to gather some feedback in our ongoing research
on integration testing of Terraform modules. The hope is that by having a
command integrated into Terraform itself it'll be easier for interested
module authors to give it a try, and also easier for us to iterate quickly
based on feedback without having to coordinate across multiple codebases.

Everything about this is subject to change even in future patch releases.
Since it's a CLI command rather than a configuration language feature it's
not using the language experiments mechanism, but generates a warning
similar to the one language experiments generate in order to be clear that

The runtime spec expects the FileMode field to only hold file permissions,
however `unix.Stat_t.Mode` contains both file type and mode.

This patch strips file type so that only file mode is included in the Device.

Thanks to Iceber Gu, who noticed the same issue in containerd and runc.

[{"sha":"50d58b592a3bc622dc850910d703d08a1f910f0f","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Migrate refresh to command views","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/50d58b592a3bc622dc850910d703d08a1f910f0f"},{"sha":"8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"internal/moduletest: Experimental module testing helpers

As part of ongoing research into Terraform testing we'd like to use an
experimental feature to validate our current understanding that expressing
tests as part of the Terraform language, as opposed to in some other
language run alongside, is a good and viable way to write practical
module integration tests.

This initial experimental incarnation of that idea is implemented as a
provider, just because that's an easier extension point for research
purposes than a first-class language feature would be. Whether this would
ultimately emerge as a provider similar to this or as custom language
constructs will be a matter for future research, if this first
experiment confirms that tests written in the Terraform language are the
best direction to take.

The previous incarnation of this experiment was an externally-developed
provider apparentlymart/testing, listed on the Terraform Registry. That
helped with showing that there are some useful tests that we can write
in the Terraform language, but integrating such a provider into Terraform
will allow us to make use of it in the also-experimental "terraform test"
command, which will follow in subsequent commits, to see how this might
fit into a development workflow.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/8330f8e991925b17c8b679943fa3824159a3a07c"},{"sha":"7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"command: Experimental "terraform test" command

This is just a prototype to gather some feedback in our ongoing research
on integration testing of Terraform modules. The hope is that by having a
command integrated into Terraform itself it'll be easier for interested
module authors to give it a try, and also easier for us to iterate quickly
based on feedback without having to coordinate across multiple codebases.

Everything about this is subject to change even in future patch releases.
Since it's a CLI command rather than a configuration language feature it's
not using the language experiments mechanism, but generates a warning
similar to the one language experiments generate in order to be clear that
backward compatibility is not guaranteed.","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/hashicorp/terraform/commits/7f783429536db18473c3299d2b516496d0b39e7e"},{"sha":"8d37a709877db9004f896db92ddc5e95837be378","author":{"name":"Martin Atkins","email":"a1bdfbfb01322b54f9edf8cea8f328c9384b211a@degeneration.co.uk"},"message":"website: Initial docs for the module integration testing experiment

Since this is still at an early phase and likely to change significantly
in future iterations, rather than attempting to guess on a suitable final
location for documenting the testing feature I've instead taken the
unusual approach of adding a new page that is explicitly about the
experiment. My expectation is that once we conclude the experiment we'll
replace this new page with a stub that just explains that there was once
an experiment and then links to whatever final feature unfolded from the
research.

The URL for this page is hard-coded into the warning message in the
"terraform test" command, so as we continue to evolve this feature in

[{"sha":"e417d796a0dc4c7206abeefd6c29ab615da9470f","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"don't add duplicate proxy provider nodes

Fix the logic to add proxy provider nodes for implicitly passed in
providers. The missing continue allowed multiple nodes satisfying the
same provider address to be added to the graph. When attaching the
providers to resources, the fist one encountered would be used, which
could change each time the graph was built.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/e417d796a0dc4c7206abeefd6c29ab615da9470f"},{"sha":"0da0b24527129c4fa89f82615b3c679968627ca3","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"provider transformer test mixing legacy stuff

Test a combination of new required_providers modules and legacy implied
providers along with providers within modules and inheritance.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/0da0b24527129c4fa89f82615b3c679968627ca3"},{"sha":"b1d8d856ca0cf275022f73ec99d2ff4641284ea7","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove ParentProviderTransformer

There is no longer any concept of a "parent provider". Inheritance of
default providers is discovered and connected in the ProviderTransformer
itself.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/NeatNerdPrime/terraform/commits/b1d8d856ca0cf275022f73ec99d2ff4641284ea7"},{"sha":"8c1703d8df67bc3cb134af58cdea0dded438d617","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"simplify the use of configuration_aliases

Now that the possibility of extra provider nodes being added is gone, we
can skip the separate handling of configuration_aliases in the
ProviderConfigTransformer. Instead of adding concrete provider nodes for
configuration_aliases (which could be surprising later as the code
evolves), we implicitly add them based on the providers being passed in

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. Now that the possibility of extra provider nodes being added is gone, we
can skip the separate handling of configuration_aliases in the
ProviderConfigTransformer. Instead of adding concrete provider nodes for
configuration_aliases (which could be surprising later as the code
evolves), we implicitly add them based on the providers being passed in
by the parent module, using the same mechanism as non-aliased providers.

Although we don't typically do configuration-level string wrangling
directly in Terraform, we delegate to several other upstream libraries
that do. These upgrades all switch to newer versions that support the
latest definitions from Unicode 13, primarily affecting operations such
as converting strings to upper/lowercase or splitting strings into
component characters (substr, reverse, etc).

The tests for the upstream libraries didn't show any regressions from
these updates, so the Unicode 13 changes seem to be backward-compatible
additions rather than significant breaking changes.

[{"sha":"e5f6b91d294d0c1260ce5079ed0192b43ccd3e82","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add Lane labels to scheduling profiler marks (#20808)

This commit changes scheduling profiler marks from a format like '--schedule-render-1' to '--schedule-render-1-Sync' (where 1 is the numeric value of the Sync lane). This will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. These are no-ops for us, but adding recognition of the event type will prevent profiles imported from e.g. Chrome Canary from throwing with an 'unrecognized event' error. (This will resolve issue #20767.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MLH-Fellowship/react/commits/e5f6b91d294d0c1260ce5079ed0192b43ccd3e82"},{"sha":"4190a34588ec0b05aac6f050ec656ec4b3f005d7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update scheduling profiler Webpack config (#20867)

Use the pre-built scheduler (which includes a check for 'window' being defined in order to load the right scheduler implementation) rather than just directly importing a version of the scheduler that relies on window. The runtime spec expects the FileMode field to only hold file permissions,
however `unix.Stat_t.Mode` contains both file type and mode.

This patch strips file type so that only file mode is included in the Device.

Thanks to Iceber Gu, who noticed the same issue in containerd and runc.

[{"sha":"04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057","author":{"name":"Lukas Geiger","email":"c177b3022030a594aa53debfd3a1bd597e06810a@gmail.com"},"message":"Prefer generator expressions over list comprehensions

This PR replaces list comprehensions that are only used as input to 
`any()` or `all()` with generator expressions. This removes the need to 
instantiate unnecessary lists if the expresion is only consumed as an 
iterator and in the case of any allows the loop to potentially exit 
early which can improve performance for long iterations.

Most of the changes are not in a hot code path so this won't noticably 
improve performance but since the change don't hurt readability I think 
they are still useful to include.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/lgeiger/tensorflow/commits/04950c7f84ec8ae238878feb6244cd88f47e3057"}]

This commit changes scheduling profiler marks from a format like '--schedule-render-1' to '--schedule-render-1-Sync' (where 1 is the numeric value of the Sync lane). This will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. These are no-ops for us, but adding recognition of the event type will prevent profiles imported from e.g. Chrome Canary from throwing with an 'unrecognized event' error. The runtime spec expects the FileMode field to only hold file permissions,
however `unix.Stat_t.Mode` contains both file type and mode.

This patch strips file type so that only file mode is included in the Device.

Thanks to Iceber Gu, who noticed the same issue in containerd and runc.

Example:
Input TF executor dialect:
%outputs, %control = tf_executor.island wraps "tf.Case"(%arg, ...) {branches = [@branch0, @branch1], ...}

lowered TFRT CoreRT dialect:
%idx_int = corert.tensorhandle_to_int32 %idx
%out_chain, %outputs = tfrt.case %idx_int [@branch0, @branch1] (%chain, ...)

Disable a Python test since TFRT doesn't support lowering v1 control flow ops ("_SwitchN" in this test).

Lowering MLIR unit test added at third_party/tensorflow/compiler/mlir/tfrt/tests/tf_to_corert/control_flow.mlir.

This commit changes scheduling profiler marks from a format like '--schedule-render-1' to '--schedule-render-1-Sync' (where 1 is the numeric value of the Sync lane). This will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. These are no-ops for us, but adding recognition of the event type will prevent profiles imported from e.g. Chrome Canary from throwing with an 'unrecognized event' error. Now that the possibility of extra provider nodes being added is gone, we
can skip the separate handling of configuration_aliases in the
ProviderConfigTransformer. Instead of adding concrete provider nodes for
configuration_aliases (which could be surprising later as the code
evolves), we implicitly add them based on the providers being passed in
by the parent module, using the same mechanism as non-aliased providers.

Although we don't typically do configuration-level string wrangling
directly in Terraform, we delegate to several other upstream libraries
that do. These upgrades all switch to newer versions that support the
latest definitions from Unicode 13, primarily affecting operations such
as converting strings to upper/lowercase or splitting strings into
component characters (substr, reverse, etc).

The tests for the upstream libraries didn't show any regressions from
these updates, so the Unicode 13 changes seem to be backward-compatible
additions rather than significant breaking changes.

(Our go.mod file had also become non-canonical in some ways, and the Go
toolchain fixed that as part of this work, causing a few extra style-only
diffs here that shouldn't cause any change in behavior.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/claytonbrown/terraform/commits/5f3fb00af5376fb3952b58da0eff6be52f920ffd"},{"sha":"c103242bef596c81171ac035511059918be3a728","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #27885 from hashicorp/jbardin/show-json

[{"sha":"e5f6b91d294d0c1260ce5079ed0192b43ccd3e82","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add Lane labels to scheduling profiler marks (#20808)

This commit changes scheduling profiler marks from a format like '--schedule-render-1' to '--schedule-render-1-Sync' (where 1 is the numeric value of the Sync lane). This will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. These are no-ops for us, but adding recognition of the event type will prevent profiles imported from e.g. Chrome Canary from throwing with an 'unrecognized event' error. (This will resolve issue #20767.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vacantthinker-forks/react/commits/e5f6b91d294d0c1260ce5079ed0192b43ccd3e82"},{"sha":"4190a34588ec0b05aac6f050ec656ec4b3f005d7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update scheduling profiler Webpack config (#20867)

Use the pre-built scheduler (which includes a check for 'window' being defined in order to load the right scheduler implementation) rather than just directly importing a version of the scheduler that relies on window. [{"sha":"6cd9552206b498ca6af04722e0749a6e4cf26a15","author":{"name":"Frederic Bastien","email":"f97faf633e0f27948feb654f3e29ab2be0f12d06@nvidia.com"},"message":"[XLA:GPU] Allows loading textual LLVM IR from a file instead of the one generated by XLA codegen.

This helps prototyping some LLVM IR without the need to change XLA code
emitter.

How to use:
- Get an module_NNNN.ir-no-opt.ll file from XLA.
- Copy that to a new file named module_NNNN.ANYTHING.ll
- Modify it to the LLVM IR that you want to prototype.
- Then pass that new file to XLA with:
  XLA_FLAGS=--xla_gpu_llvm_ir_file=module_NNNN.ANYTHING.ll

This can be used with Tensorflow directly, but also with
replay_computation or run_hlo_module. You should make sure that both run
are on the same computer in the exact same configuration. Otherwise
anything can happens.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/nouiz/tensorflow/commits/6cd9552206b498ca6af04722e0749a6e4cf26a15"}]

[{"sha":"e5f6b91d294d0c1260ce5079ed0192b43ccd3e82","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Add Lane labels to scheduling profiler marks (#20808)

This commit changes scheduling profiler marks from a format like '--schedule-render-1' to '--schedule-render-1-Sync' (where 1 is the numeric value of the Sync lane). This will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. These are no-ops for us, but adding recognition of the event type will prevent profiles imported from e.g. Chrome Canary from throwing with an 'unrecognized event' error. (This will resolve issue #20767.)","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/e5f6b91d294d0c1260ce5079ed0192b43ccd3e82"},{"sha":"4190a34588ec0b05aac6f050ec656ec4b3f005d7","author":{"name":"Brian Vaughn","email":"59942a8ec08225673b377c556396ca24baabd1b2@fb.com"},"message":"Update scheduling profiler Webpack config (#20867)

Use the pre-built scheduler (which includes a check for 'window' being defined in order to load the right scheduler implementation) rather than just directly importing a version of the scheduler that relies on window. Since the scheduling profiler's code runs partially in a web worker, it can't rely on window.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/miqdigital/react/commits/4190a34588ec0b05aac6f050ec656ec4b3f005d7"}]

Fix the logic to add proxy provider nodes for implicitly passed in
providers. The missing continue allowed multiple nodes satisfying the
same provider address to be added to the graph. When attaching the
providers to resources, the fist one encountered would be used, which
could change each time the graph was built.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/e417d796a0dc4c7206abeefd6c29ab615da9470f"},{"sha":"0da0b24527129c4fa89f82615b3c679968627ca3","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"provider transformer test mixing legacy stuff

providers along with providers within modules and inheritance.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/0da0b24527129c4fa89f82615b3c679968627ca3"},{"sha":"b1d8d856ca0cf275022f73ec99d2ff4641284ea7","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove ParentProviderTransformer

There is no longer any concept of a "parent provider". Inheritance of
default providers is discovered and connected in the ProviderTransformer
itself.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/b1d8d856ca0cf275022f73ec99d2ff4641284ea7"},{"sha":"8c1703d8df67bc3cb134af58cdea0dded438d617","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"simplify the use of configuration_aliases

Now that the possibility of extra provider nodes being added is gone, we
can skip the separate handling of configuration_aliases in the
ProviderConfigTransformer. Instead of adding concrete provider nodes for
configuration_aliases (which could be surprising later as the code
evolves), we implicitly add them based on the providers being passed in
by the parent module, using the same mechanism as non-aliased providers.

We can know that the `providers` map will be populated, because the
provider structures are validated while loading the configuration.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pecigonzalo/terraform/commits/8c1703d8df67bc3cb134af58cdea0dded438d617"},{"sha":"dd5227a3bee9cadefa4f1bdae6f28946ed33d130","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"provider transformer tests

This commit changes scheduling profiler marks from a format like '--schedule-render-1' to '--schedule-render-1-Sync' (where 1 is the numeric value of the Sync lane). This will enable the profiler itself to show more meaningful labels for updates and render work.

The commit also refactors and adds additional tests for the scheduling profiler package.

It also updates the preprocessor to 'support' instant events. These are no-ops for us, but adding recognition of the event type will prevent profiles imported from e.g. Chrome Canary from throwing with an 'unrecognized event' error.
